            <div type="glosses">
                <note xml:id="THEDESCENTGLOSS" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x201C;The Descent&#x201D; (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSVIII">MS VIII</title>; 
                    <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title> [<date when="1903">1903</date>])&#x2014;</hi><persName corresp="#WGC">W. G. Collingwood</persName> 
                    omitted this poem from his version of the <title type="composite" corresp="#JRACCOUNTTOUR">&#x201C;Account&#x201D;</title>. <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName> 
                    gives no explanation for the omission, which may have been a mere oversight; and the editors of the <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE">Library Edition</title> 
                    restored the poem in their version, also without commenting on the text&#x02BC;s omission from the <date when="1891">1891</date> version. 
                    <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s intended place for the poem is clear, based on the cluster of titles listed in his 
                    <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_toc_msviii.php#ACCOUNTTOCDESCENT">Proposed Plan for the Continuation of the Account of a Tour on the Continent</ref>, 
                    which traces the crossing of the <geogName corresp="#ALPS">Alps</geogName>, and which is modeled on a sequence of poems in <persName corresp="#SR">Samuel Rogers</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    <title type="poem" corresp="ROGERSITALY"><hi rend="italic">Italy</hi></title>. See the contextual notes to <title type="poem" corresp="JRTHEDESCENT">&#x201C;The Descent&#x201D;</title>.</p></note>
            </div>
